Edit platform/plugin-tools/src/commands/build.ts — modify the wrapperCode template string in bundleIIFE(). The current wrapper code is at lines 256-266. It imports the plugin, sets up __openTabs.adapters, calls teardown on existing adapter, deletes old entry, and registers new one. The new wrapper needs to:

1. AFTER `adapters[name] = plugin` (line 265): call `plugin.onActivate()` if it exists, wrapped in try-catch.

2. BEFORE that line, modify the teardown of the OLD adapter: if the old adapter has onDeactivate, call it BEFORE teardown. The current code (lines 261-262) only calls existing.teardown(). Change to: if (existing.onDeactivate) try { existing.onDeactivate() } catch(e) { ... }; if (existing.teardown) try { existing.teardown() } catch(e) { ... };

3. AFTER adapter registration + onActivate: if plugin.onNavigate exists, set up URL change detection:
   - Save originals: const origPushState = history.pushState; const origReplaceState = history.replaceState;
   - let lastUrl = location.href;
   - const checkUrl = () => { const newUrl = location.href; if (newUrl !== lastUrl) { lastUrl = newUrl; try { plugin.onNavigate(newUrl); } catch(e) { console.warn(...); } } };
   - history.pushState = function(...args) { origPushState.apply(this, args); checkUrl(); };
   - history.replaceState = function(...args) { origReplaceState.apply(this, args); checkUrl(); };
   - window.addEventListener('popstate', checkUrl);
   - window.addEventListener('hashchange', checkUrl);
   - Store cleanup refs on the adapter object (e.g., adapter.__cleanupNavigation) so teardown can restore originals and remove listeners.

4. AFTER adapter registration: if plugin.onToolInvocationStart or plugin.onToolInvocationEnd exists, wrap each tool.handle():
   - for (const tool of plugin.tools) { const origHandle = tool.handle; tool.handle = async function(params) { const startTime = performance.now(); try { plugin.onToolInvocationStart?.(tool.name); } catch(e) { console.warn(...); } let success = true; try { const result = await origHandle.call(this, params); return result; } catch(err) { success = false; throw err; } finally { const duration = performance.now() - startTime; try { plugin.onToolInvocationEnd?.(tool.name, success, duration); } catch(e) { console.warn(...); } } }; }
   - IMPORTANT: This wrapping must happen BEFORE Object.freeze(tool) in the hashAndFreeze snippet (line 376). Currently the freeze happens in a separate appended snippet. Since the tool wrapping happens in the main IIFE and the freeze happens in the hashAndFreeze snippet (appended after), the ordering is correct.

5. Update the teardown wrapper: the adapter's teardown needs to also call onDeactivate and clean up navigation listeners. Modify the existing teardown pattern so that when THIS adapter is later torn down (by a future re-injection), onDeactivate fires first, then navigation cleanup, then teardown.
   - One approach: wrap the plugin's original teardown in a new function that calls onDeactivate first, then cleans up navigation, then calls original teardown. Assign this wrapper as adapter.teardown.
   - E.g.: const origTeardown = plugin.teardown?.bind(plugin); plugin.teardown = function() { try { plugin.onDeactivate?.(); } catch(e) { ... } if (adapter.__cleanupNavigation) adapter.__cleanupNavigation(); if (origTeardown) origTeardown(); };

The key architectural insight: all hook wiring happens in the IIFE wrapper that bundleIIFE generates. The SDK only defines the interface. The build tool generates the runtime code that actually calls the hooks. This is the correct place because the IIFE runs in the page context where all the DOM APIs (history, events) are available.

Two files to modify:

1. plugins/e2e-test/src/index.ts — add all lifecycle hooks to E2eTestPlugin:
   ```
   override onActivate(): void {
     (globalThis as any).__opentabs_onActivate_called = true;
   }

   override onDeactivate(): void {
     (globalThis as any).__opentabs_onDeactivate_called = true;
   }

   override onNavigate(url: string): void {
     const g = globalThis as any;
     if (!g.__opentabs_onNavigate_urls) g.__opentabs_onNavigate_urls = [];
     g.__opentabs_onNavigate_urls.push(url);
   }

   override onToolInvocationStart(toolName: string): void {
     const g = globalThis as any;
     if (!g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_start) g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_start = [];
     g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_start.push(toolName);
   }

   override onToolInvocationEnd(toolName: string, success: boolean, durationMs: number): void {
     const g = globalThis as any;
     if (!g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_end) g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_end = [];
     g.__opentabs_tool_invocation_end.push({ toolName, success, durationMs });
   }
   ```
   Then rebuild the e2e-test plugin: cd plugins/e2e-test && bun install && bun run build (need updated SDK first).

2. Create e2e/lifecycle-hooks.e2e.ts — new E2E test file:
   - Use existing fixtures (mcpServer, extensionContext, testServer, mcpClient)
   - Use helpers (setupToolTest, callToolExpectSuccess, waitFor, waitForToolResult)
   - Test structure:
     ```
     test.describe('Lifecycle hooks', () => {
       test('onActivate fires when adapter is injected', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
         const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
         const activated = await page.evaluate(() => (globalThis as any).__opentabs_onActivate_called);
         expect(activated).toBe(true);
       });

       test('onNavigate fires on pushState URL change', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
         const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
         await page.evaluate(() => history.pushState({}, '', '/new-path'));
         await page.waitForTimeout(100); // allow event to propagate
         const urls = await page.evaluate(() => (globalThis as any).__opentabs_onNavigate_urls);
         expect(urls).toContainEqual(expect.stringContaining('/new-path'));
       });

       test('onToolInvocationStart and onToolInvocationEnd fire around tool calls', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
         const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
         await callToolExpectSuccess(mcpClient, mcpServer, 'e2e-test_echo', { message: 'test' });
         const starts = await page.evaluate(() => (globalThis as any).__opentabs_tool_invocation_start);
         expect(starts).toContain('echo');
         const ends = await page.evaluate(() => (globalThis as any).__opentabs_tool_invocation_end);
         expect(ends).toEqual(expect.arrayContaining([expect.objectContaining({ toolName: 'echo', success: true })]));
         expect(ends[0].durationMs).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(0);
       });

       test('onToolInvocationEnd reports failure for failing tools', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
         const page = await setupToolTest(mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext, mcpClient);
         // Call the failing tool — it will return an error through tool dispatch
         await mcpClient.callTool('e2e-test_failing_tool', {});
         const ends = await page.evaluate(() => (globalThis as any).__opentabs_tool_invocation_end);
         expect(ends).toEqual(expect.arrayContaining([expect.objectContaining({ toolName: 'failing_tool', success: false })]));
       });

       test('onDeactivate fires on adapter re-injection (plugin.update)', async ({ ... }) => {
         // This is trickier — need to trigger a plugin.update which re-injects.
         // Use hot reload or direct plugin.update message to force re-injection.
         // After re-injection, the OLD adapter's onDeactivate should have fired.
         // Since onDeactivate is wired through teardown, and teardown is called
         // on re-injection (forceReinject=true), the marker should be set.
         // Check __opentabs_onDeactivate_called after triggering plugin.update.
       });
     });
     ```
   - For the onDeactivate test, the approach is: (a) setup the tool test (adapter injected, onActivate fires), (b) trigger a hot reload on the MCP server which sends sync.full → extension re-injects adapters with forceReinject=true → old adapter teardown is called → onDeactivate fires before teardown → new adapter registered → new onActivate fires. Check __opentabs_onDeactivate_called. Note: since the constructor clears teardown markers, use __opentabs_onDeactivate_called which is NOT cleared by the constructor (add it to the list of markers NOT cleared).

   IMPORTANT: The e2e-test plugin must be rebuilt with the updated SDK BEFORE running E2E tests. The build order is: (1) build platform packages (includes plugin-sdk), (2) publish SDK, (3) update e2e-test plugin deps, (4) rebuild e2e-test plugin, (5) run E2E tests. Since this is in development, we can use a local path override or workspace link temporarily.
